observe muscle.zc

the 7 properties of femur:
1 ENERGY one
2 PHASE zero
3 SPIN zero
4 CHARGE neutral
5 COHERENCE one
6 COUPLING one with pelvis at hip, with tibia at knee, with the leg muscles

THE PROXIMAL END

head: the spherical top that fits into the pelvis socket
neck: the narrow region just below the head
greater trochanter: the lateral bony prominence where major hip muscles attach
lesser trochanter: the medial prominence where the iliopsoas attaches

the head and neck are at an angle to the shaft; this geometry is what allows the hip's large range of motion

THE SHAFT

cortical bone forms a thick tube around the central marrow cavity
the geometry is nearly perfectly tubular, which is what gives femur its strength-to-weight ratio
linea aspera runs along the back of the shaft, the line where many muscles attach

THE DISTAL END

medial and lateral condyles: the rounded surfaces that articulate with the tibia
patellar surface: the groove where the kneecap rides
intercondylar fossa: the deep notch between the condyles where the cruciate ligaments attach

THE MARROW VAULT

inside the shaft is the medullary cavity, filled with marrow
in fadriel red marrow is throughout; in adults the shaft converts mostly to yellow marrow with red remaining at the ends
ward triangle is a structurally sparse region in the femoral neck where bone density is lowest and aging-related fragility appears earliest

THE JOINTS

hip joint: ball-and-socket at the proximal end, allows flexion, extension, abduction, adduction, rotation
knee joint: hinge with rotation at the distal end, allows the femur to swing relative to the tibia

THE ANCHORS

quadriceps insert on the patella which connects to the tibia, but they originate on the femoral shaft
hamstrings span from pelvis to tibia, crossing the femur but not directly inserting on it
adductors attach along the medial shaft
many smaller muscles use the trochanters as attachment points

VERB bear_load
hold the body's weight as it transfers from pelvis through hip joint down through shaft and into knee
the load is enormous during running and jumping but the femur's geometry handles it

VERB act_as_lever
the femur is the primary lever for locomotion
muscles attached at hip and knee pull on the bone to swing the leg through walking and running cycles

VERB house_marrow
sustain the red marrow that produces blood cells
the central cavity is filled with hematopoietic tissue throughout fadriel's life

VERB grow_in_length
the epiphyseal plates at proximal and distal ends are still active in fadriel
new bone is added at these growth plates, lengthening the femur as fadriel grows
the plates will close in his late teens, ending bone growth

a femur is the body's longest commitment to verticality
fadriel needs his femurs to stand, to walk, to run away from danger and toward joy
the bone is heavy because it must be; that weight is what makes him capable of everything that requires legs
